
Catalyst Deactivation and Carbon Deposition in Integrated Sabatier Reactors for Mars ISRU Methane Production

Version 6.0 


Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Date: April 2026


---

Abstract

The production of methane propellant via the Sabatier reaction on Mars is a cornerstone technology for human exploration, yet current reactor designs face critical lifetime limitations due to catalyst deactivation from coking, sintering, and trace contaminant poisoning under Martian atmospheric pressure (600 Pa) and solar power intermittency. This work presents a comprehensive, integrated approach to address these challenges through a synergistic combination of advanced materials, multi-physics modeling, and autonomous artificial intelligence control. We propose a graded-bed membrane reactor architecture incorporating NaA zeolite or UiO-66-NH₂ mixed-matrix membranes for continuous in-situ water removal, a corona-discharge electrostatic precipitator for low-power dust filtration, and a novel "catalyst health mapping" framework that spatially resolves cumulative degradation mechanisms. A Bayesian Optimal Experimental Design methodology, augmented with multi-objective Bayesian Optimization, is employed to efficiently parameterize low-pressure kinetics and deactivation pathways from accelerated aging campaigns. These data inform a high-fidelity computational fluid dynamics model with Dusty Gas Model transport, which is subsequently distilled into a hybrid Physics-Informed Neural Network–Gaussian Process surrogate for real-time state estimation and uncertainty quantification. The control layer leverages a Lyapunov-constrained Safe Reinforcement Learning policy, structured as an operation-recipe optimizer, that guarantees closed-loop stability while autonomously managing H₂:CO₂ ratio, space velocity, and thermal management across 30-sol power transients and start-up/shutdown cycles. The system is designed for zero-consumable, 10,000-hour operation with full N+1 redundancy. The proposed five-phase research plan culminates in a 500-hour integrated demonstration under combined Martian stressors, targeting >99% methane conversion, >98% selectivity, and >80% catalyst activity retention with fully autonomous fault handling and regeneration. The deliverables include open-source kinetic libraries, validated AI control policies, and a TRL 5–6 flight-readiness assessment aligned with NASA's stated ISRU priorities on scaling, start-up/shutdown, and catalyst lifetime, establishing a definitive pathway toward reliable, autonomous propellant production on Mars.

