1. Mathematics Background

The Sabatier reaction at Martian surface conditions (P = 600\,\mathrm{Pa}) is governed by the reversible exothermic equilibrium:

\mathrm{CO_2 + 4H_2 \rightleftharpoons CH_4 + 2H_2O} \quad (\Delta H^\circ = -165\,\mathrm{kJ/mol})

The temperature-dependent equilibrium constant is

K_p(T) = \exp\left(\frac{165000}{RT} - 32.8\right)

where partial pressures are in Pa and T is in Kelvin. At these low pressures, the mean free path of gas molecules becomes comparable to the pore diameter of the catalyst support (typically 10–50 nm). Consequently, the Knudsen number Kn > 0.1, and conventional Fickian diffusion fails to describe species transport. We therefore adopt the Dusty Gas Model (DGM), the gold standard for porous media transport, which unifies Knudsen diffusion, molecular diffusion, and viscous (Darcy) flow into a single flux framework.

1.1 Intrinsic Kinetics, Selectivity, and Catalyst Health Mapping

The intrinsic methane formation rate follows an extended Langmuir-Hinshelwood-Hougen-Watson (LHHW) formulation that accounts for competitive adsorption of oxygen and chlorine species from perchlorate electrolysis, as well as the simultaneous Reverse Water-Gas Shift (RWGS) reaction:

r_{\mathrm{CH_4}} = \frac{k_s(T) \, P_{\mathrm{H_2}}^\alpha P_{\mathrm{CO_2}}^\beta}{\left(1 + K_{\mathrm{CO}} P_{\mathrm{CO}} + K_{\mathrm{H_2O}} P_{\mathrm{H_2O}} + K_{\mathrm{O_2}} P_{\mathrm{O_2}}^{0.5} + K_{\mathrm{Cl}} P_{\mathrm{HCl}}\right)^2}

All adsorption constants K_i(T) and the rate constant k_s(T) follow Arrhenius forms. The selectivity of methane over carbon monoxide is defined by the dimensionless metric:

\mathcal{S}(T) = \frac{r_{\mathrm{CH_4}}}{r_{\mathrm{CH_4}} + r_{\mathrm{CO}}}

where r_{\mathrm{CO}} is the net rate of CO formation from the RWGS reaction. The denominator of the LHHW expression explicitly includes the CO inhibition term (K_{\mathrm{CO}}P_{\mathrm{CO}}), ensuring that the kinetic model captures the competitive adsorption that suppresses methane yield at elevated temperatures.

Catalyst health \mathcal{H}(\mathbf{x},t) \in [0,1] is defined as the spatially resolved metric:

\mathcal{H}(\mathbf{x},t) = w_1 a(\mathbf{x},t) + w_2 \left(1 - \frac{S_{\mathrm{loss}}(\mathbf{x},t)}{S_0}\right) - w_3 \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}(\mathbf{x},t) - w_4 \left(\frac{T(\mathbf{x},t) - T_{\mathrm{safe}}}{\Delta T_{\mathrm{crit}}}\right)^2

with weights w_i calibrated via Bayesian inference on post-mortem data (XRD, TEM, TPO, XPS).

1.2 Deactivation Dynamics and Regeneration

Activity evolves according to a state-dependent power-law model:

\frac{\partial a}{\partial t} = -k_d(T, \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}, C_{\mathrm{coke}}) \, a^{m(T, \theta_{\mathrm{Cl}}, C_{\mathrm{coke}})} \, C_{\mathrm{coke}}(\mathbf{x},t)

Sintering follows:

\frac{dS}{dt} = -k_{\mathrm{sint}}(T) \, S^n

Mild H₂-rich regeneration pulses (H₂:CO₂ = 6:1 at 300–320 °C) are included as a recoverable term in the activity ODE, with the regeneration rate modeled as:

\frac{\partial a_{\mathrm{recover}}}{\partial t} = k_{\mathrm{reg}}(T) \, C_{\mathrm{coke}} \, a

1.3 Governing Transport: The Dusty Gas Model (DGM)

At Martian pressures (600 Pa), Fickian diffusion fails due to strong Knudsen effects. The Dusty Gas Model is the gold standard for porous media transport, unifying Knudsen diffusion, molecular diffusion, and viscous (Darcy) flow into a single flux framework. The molar flux \mathbf{N}_i of species i is given by:

\frac{\mathbf{N}_i}{D_{K,i}^{\mathrm{eff}}} + \sum_{j \neq i} \frac{y_j \mathbf{N}_i - y_i \mathbf{N}_j}{D_{ij}^{\mathrm{eff}}} = -\frac{P}{RT} \nabla y_i - \frac{y_i}{RT}\left(1 + \frac{B_0 P}{\mu D_{K,i}^{\mathrm{eff}}}\right) \nabla P

where:

· B_0 is the permeability coefficient (m²),
· \mu is the gas mixture viscosity,
· D_{K,i}^{\mathrm{eff}} is the effective Knudsen diffusivity,
· D_{ij}^{\mathrm{eff}} is the effective binary molecular diffusivity.

The term (1 + B_0 P / \mu D_{K,i}^{\mathrm{eff}}) captures the transition between Knudsen flow and Poiseuille (viscous) flow. This formulation is critical because pressure drops across a 1-meter catalyst bed can exceed 10–20% of the total Martian pressure, which standard Fickian diffusion models cannot resolve.

The 2D axisymmetric conservation equations for species mass and energy are:

\frac{\partial}{\partial t}(\rho Y_i) + \nabla \cdot (\rho \mathbf{u} Y_i) = \nabla \cdot (\rho D_{i,\mathrm{eff}} \nabla Y_i) + R_i(a,T)

\rho C_p \frac{\partial T}{\partial t} + \rho C_p \mathbf{u} \cdot \nabla T = \nabla \cdot (k_{\mathrm{eff}} \nabla T) + \sum_j (-\Delta H_j) R_j

The membrane water flux boundary condition is:

J_{\mathrm{H_2O}} = \Pi(T) \left( p_{\mathrm{H_2O,feed}} - p_{\mathrm{H_2O,perm}} \right)

where \Pi(T) is characterized at 600 Pa for NaA zeolite or UiO-66-NH₂ mixed-matrix membranes.

1.4 Bayesian Optimal Experimental Design (BOED)

Parameters are treated as random variables; multi-objective Bayesian Optimization (Expected Hypervolume Improvement) actively selects test conditions to map the Pareto front of CH₄ yield versus deactivation rate. This approach, validated in recent catalytic reaction studies, dramatically reduces the experimental burden while providing rigorous uncertainty quantification.

1.5 Model Benchmarking

All CFD models are benchmarked against 2022–2025 shell-and-tube reactor studies of carbon deposition and thermal degradation.

