2. System Architecture and Design

The integrated Sabatier reactor is a modular, membrane-augmented fixed-bed system sized for MAV-scale propellant production (0.55–0.88 kg h⁻¹ CH₄, 4-crew mission). Total mass <100 kg, specific energy <1 kWh kg⁻¹ CH₄. Architecture emphasizes zero-consumable operation, N+1 redundancy, and full autonomy.

2.1 Core Reactor Module

· Cylindrical vessel (ID 150 mm, length 800 mm) in 600 Pa chamber.
· Graded catalyst bed: Ru/Al₂O₃ inlet zone → Ni-CeO₂-ZrO₂ core-shell outlet zone. The Ru-rich inlet provides fast initial kinetics and chlorine tolerance, while the Ni-based outlet maximizes coking resistance and selectivity.
· Membrane tubes: NaA zeolite or UiO-66-NH₂ mixed-matrix composites for in-situ H₂O removal. A 2025 study demonstrated that such a membrane Sabatier system achieves >99% CO₂ conversion and a CH₄ space-time yield of 1947 mmol g⁻¹ h⁻¹ with zero deactivation over 10 days of continuous operation, while maintaining robustness under intermittent power supplies.
· Dust mitigation: Corona-discharge electrostatic precipitator (ESP) at CO₂ intake. A 2025 IEEE study established that stable corona discharges can be sustained in CO₂ at 5–10 mbar (500–1000 Pa), enabling 94–99% particle removal efficiency with negligible pressure drop. A low-frequency vibration actuator and H₂ pressure-swing purge provide additional dust shedding. The AI controller monitors the mass spectrometer baseline for dust-induced signal drift and adjusts vibration frequency to avoid harmonic interference.
· Thermal management: Radial heat pipes + phase-change buffers (paraffin/salt hydrate) for 30-sol transients; 16-point Type-K thermocouple array + ΔP + miniaturized quadrupole MS.

2.2 Feed and Purification Subsystem

· CO₂ from Martian atmosphere (compressed, dried, ESP-filtered).
· H₂ from solid-oxide electrolysis of perchlorate water, pre-treated by Cu/ZnO/Al₂O₃ Cl scrubber + 5Å molecular sieve.
· Closed water recycle loop.

2.3 AI-Enabled Autonomous Control Layer

· Hybrid PINN-GP surrogate: PINN enforces PDE residuals; GP quantifies epistemic uncertainty. <100 ms inference on embedded hardware. Outputs 2D temperature/coking/health fields from sparse sensors.
· Lyapunov-constrained Safe RL policy: The PPO agent is constrained by a Lyapunov candidate function L(s) = -V(s) and L(s,a) = -Q(s,a), where constraints enforce positivity of the Lyapunov function and non-positive time derivatives (\dot{L}(s) \leq 0). This guarantees monotonic convergence to the safe setpoint. A 2025 study demonstrated that these Lyapunov constraints significantly improved control performance across multiple RL algorithms, yielding higher cumulative rewards, reduced overshoot, and decreased variability. The policy acts as an operation-recipe optimizer for baseline PI/MPC setpoints (H₂:CO₂ ratio, GHSV, coolant duty).
· LSTM + attention fault classifier: Distinguishes reversible coking from irreversible damage and triggers maintenance-mode regeneration or N+1 failover.
· N+1 Failover Logic: The system continuously monitors the catalyst health metric \mathcal{H}(\mathbf{x},t) and the GP uncertainty bounds. A failover to a parallel reactor train is triggered if either: (1) \mathcal{H} falls below a critical threshold (e.g., 0.6) in any spatial region, or (2) the GP predictive uncertainty exceeds a predefined limit, indicating that the surrogate model is extrapolating into an unvalidated regime. Upon failover, the offline reactor undergoes a controlled shutdown with dry purge, and the AI scheduler reallocates production targets to the remaining operational trains.
· Training via domain randomization + physics-based noise for robust sim-to-real transfer.

2.4 Power and Thermal Integration

Coupled to Perseverance-derived solar forecast emulator; explicit autonomous start-up/shutdown logic, including a dry purge protocol (pure H₂ or recycled CO₂ sweep to remove residual moisture before shutdown), directly addresses NASA's identified priority of proper start-up and shutdown sequences.

